programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: City slickers Glen and Kate were delighted when they found 19 windswept acres near the seaside town of Inverloch on Victoria's south coast, where they intend to opt out for a simpler lifestyle. The plan for their new house was for something completely untested: a design based on a barchan sand dune, or an arc-shaped sand ridge. The idea for the shape came first, conceived not from the floor up but from the form down, and that meant working out a floor plan to fit the crescent shape. Inside, seven free-standing rammed earth walls separate the spaces and help to support a 'ring-beam' of super-strong laminated timber that encircles the entire perimeter and props up a grand vaulted ceiling. This is an adventurous and challenging undertaking, and the couple face many compromises as they build what is quickly dubbed 'the UFO house'. Experiments by their very nature are often open-ended and costly, and this one is no exception. Will Glen and Kate get through this complex and difficult construction to realise their original concept, or will they be forced to trim and modify because curves simply cost too much?

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Hosted by leading Australian architect Peter Maddison, the fourth series of Grand Designs Australia follows self-builders as they transform their elaborate designs into practical living space. As a brick-layer, Greg has spent most of his adult life building houses for other people. Now, after dreaming about it for more than 20 years, he's building one for himself out of the materials he's most passionate about - bricks. He and partner Emma are ripping down their inner-city townhouse in a South Melbourne laneway to build a three-level home in which to raise their young son Archie. They're also giving extended family living a go, assigning the entire ground floor of their new house to Emma's parents, who are contributing to the budget. Trustingly, Emma's parents have left the design of the house completely to Greg, who plans to be as creative as possible with his beloved bricks, which will be custom designed and painted by hand. His appreciation of craftsmanship is old-fashioned but his unique, industrial design sensibility is very contemporary, with much of the house made from recycled materials found at junkyards. But hand-made equals time-consuming, and Greg is under added pressure to move the family in, as he battles to get the in-laws' ground level finished. Plus, living with extended family is new territory for all of them. Can they survive the building process and live harmoniously in the same house?(n)

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: City slickers Glen and Kate were delighted when they found 19 windswept acres near the seaside town of Inverloch on Victoria's south coast, where they intend to opt out for a simpler lifestyle. The plan for their new house was for something completely untested: a design based on a barchan sand dune, or an arc-shaped sand ridge. The idea for the shape came first, conceived not from the floor up but from the form down, and that meant working out a floor plan to fit the crescent shape. Inside, seven free-standing rammed earth walls separate the spaces and help to support a 'ring-beam' of super-strong laminated timber that encircles the entire perimeter and props up a grand vaulted ceiling. This is an adventurous and challenging undertaking, and the couple face many compromises as they build what is quickly dubbed 'the UFO house'. Experiments by their very nature are often open-ended and costly, and this one is no exception. Will Glen and Kate get through this complex and difficult construction to realise their original concept, or will they be forced to trim and modify because curves simply cost too much?

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Hosted by leading Australian architect Peter Maddison, the fourth series of Grand Designs Australia follows self-builders as they transform their elaborate designs into practical living space. As a brick-layer, Greg has spent most of his adult life building houses for other people. Now, after dreaming about it for more than 20 years, he's building one for himself out of the materials he's most passionate about - bricks. He and partner Emma are ripping down their inner-city townhouse in a South Melbourne laneway to build a three-level home in which to raise their young son Archie. They're also giving extended family living a go, assigning the entire ground floor of their new house to Emma's parents, who are contributing to the budget. Trustingly, Emma's parents have left the design of the house completely to Greg, who plans to be as creative as possible with his beloved bricks, which will be custom designed and painted by hand. His appreciation of craftsmanship is old-fashioned but his unique, industrial design sensibility is very contemporary, with much of the house made from recycled materials found at junkyards. But hand-made equals time-consuming, and Greg is under added pressure to move the family in, as he battles to get the in-laws' ground level finished. Plus, living with extended family is new territory for all of them. Can they survive the building process and live harmoniously in the same house?(n)
